05762nam a22007935i 9780823268504DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232685047 a10.1515/97808232685042doi  a(DE-B1597)554914  a(OCoLC)960165512  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPS3552.A45bZ813 2016eb 7aLIT0040402bisacsh04a818.54092231 aPavlić, Ed, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWho Can Afford to Improvise? :bJames Baldwin and Black Music, the Lyric and the Listeners /cEd Pavlić. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. “To the listeners, for those that have an ear for this” -- tBOOK I. The Uses of the Blues -- t1. “Not the country we’re sitting in now” -- t2. Blues Constants, Jazz Changes -- t3. “Making words do something” -- tBOOK II. The Uses of the Lyric -- t4. Billie Holiday: Radical Lyricist -- t5. Dinah Washington’s Blues and the Trans- Digressive Ocean -- t6. “But Amen is the price” -- tBOOK III. “For you I was a flame” -- t7. On Camden Row -- t8. Speechless in San Francisco -- t9. “In a way they must . . .” -- t10. “Shades cannot be fixed” -- tConclusion. -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMore than a quarter-century after his death, James Baldwin remains an unparalleled figure in American literature and African American cultural politics. In Who Can Afford to Improvise? Ed Pavlić offers an unconventional, lyrical, and accessible meditation on the life, writings, and legacy of James Baldwin and their relationship to the lyric tradition in black music, from gospel and blues to jazz and R&B. Based on unprecedented access to private correspondence, unpublished manuscripts and attuned to a musically inclined poet’s skill in close listening, Who Can Afford to Improvise? frames a new narrative of James Baldwin’s work and life. The route retraces the full arc of Baldwin’s passage across the pages and stages of his career according to his constant interactions with black musical styles, recordings, and musicians.Presented in three books — or movements — the first listens to Baldwin, in the initial months of his most intense visibility in May 1963 and the publication of The Fire Next Time. It introduces the key terms of his lyrical aesthetic and identifies the shifting contours of Baldwin’s career from his early work as a reviewer for left-leaning journals in the 1940s to his last published and unpublished works from the mid-1980s. Book II listens with Baldwin and ruminates on the recorded performances of Billie Holiday and Dinah Washington, singers whose message and methods were closely related to his developing world view. It concludes with the first detailed account of “The Hallelujah Chorus,” a performance from July 1, 1973, in which Baldwin shared the stage at Carnegie Hall with Ray Charles. Finally, in Book III, Pavlić reverses our musically inflected reconsideration of Baldwin’s voice, projecting it into the contemporary moment and reading its impact on everything from the music of Amy Winehouse, to the street performances of Turf Feinz, and the fire of racial oppression and militarization against black Americans in the 21st century.Always with an ear close to the music, and avoiding the safe box of celebration, Who Can Afford to Improvise? enables a new kind of “lyrical travel” with the instructive clarity and the open-ended mystery Baldwin’s work invokes into the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aMusic and li